commitResults.messageTitle: Initial commit because I forgot to commit the Level-1 in the previous version, and I followed some guide on StackOverFlow to rebase - and then i encountered some errors.
Level-0: Initial commit that simply greets the user and exits.
Level-1: Improve the skeletal version of Duke so that it echos commands entered by the user, and exits when the user types the command bye.
Level-2: Add the ability to store whatever text entered by the user and display them back to the user when requested.

Level-3: changed the switch-case construct to if-else, and added a new Task class that was lifted off course site. Add the ability to mark tasks as done and the ability to change the status back to not done.
Level-4: Add support for tracking three types of tasks: ToDos, Events, Deadlines. Changed all the variables in each class to be a private variable. No error handling yet.
A-TextUiTesting: Use the input/output redirection technique to semi-automate the testing of Duke.

Add assertion checks for taskCounts, inputString, and UI initialization
commitResults.messageBody:
Previously, the application did not explicitly check for negative
values in taskCounts or inputString, nor did it verify that the UI was
properly initialized. This could lead to unexpected behavior or errors
if negative values were used or if the UI was accessed before being
fully initialized.

Introduce assert statements to validate that taskCounts and inputString
are not negative, and to ensure that the UI is not null before it is
used. This approach uses runtime checks to guard against invalid
states, providing a clearer error message and preventing further
execution in case of configuration errors.

This method was chosen because it allows for feedback during
development and testing, making it easier to identify and
correct issues related to improper data or UI handling.
Assert statements are simple to implement and effective for these kinds
of invariant checks that might be caused by programmer error.

These changes are part of ongoing efforts to improve code robustness
and error handling. Further validation may be added as necessary based
on future requirements or additional lectures.

commitResults.messageTitle: Modify to comply with Happy Paths
commitResults.messageBody:
Enhance happy path coverage in tests and functionality to
improve code quality

Until now, there is no standardisation in terms of how
happy paths are being programmed.

Implement adjustments to solidify the happy paths for handling dirty
user input. Standardise to implement "Happy Paths" to be after the
"if"-s clauses.

Opting for a thorough validation of happy paths allow confirmation
that functionalities are robust. It also helps in identifying
overlooked issues that might not emerge during
standard error and edge case testing. The emphasis on happy paths aims
to mirror typical user interactions closely, therefore enhancing
the overall quality of the application.

Additionally, these changes are accompanied by documentation updates to
improve general code quality.

commitResults.messageTitle: Long methods in DataStorage.java
commitResults.messageBody:
DataStorage.java contain methods that are excessively long,
making it hard to read and maintain.

Long methods can obscure the logic and make it challenging to
identify reusable components or debug.

Let's extract distinct blocks of logic from these long methods
into smaller, and more manageable methods.

Refactoring for better code structure does not alter the
functionality but significantly enhances the ease of future
modifications and comprehension.

This approach follows best practices in software development
as discussed in the Code Quality guidelines.

Refactor code for both list and find method
commitResults.messageBody:
Task listing and finding functionalities share significant code
duplication, including the filtering logic.

Code duplication across task listing and finding methods
hampers code maintainability.

Let's consolidate the logic and make use of lambda expressions.

Using lambda is preferable over traditional loops because it makes the
code much cleaner to read.

Refer to this webpage for more information about lambdas
https://nus-cs2103-ay2324s2.github.io/website/schedule/week5
